INSERT INTO public.theory_quiz_bank (course_id, question, reference_answer) VALUES
('203ee6ac-e5c8-4644-bb3c-855884ba8de4', 'What is a key-value store? Give an example.', 'A key-value store is the simplest NoSQL database where every item is stored as an attribute name (or "key") together with its value. Example: Redis or Amazon DynamoDB.'),
('203ee6ac-e5c8-4644-bb3c-855884ba8de4', 'What is a document database? Give an example (e.g., MongoDB).', 'A document database stores data in documents (like JSON, BSON, or XML) rather than rows and columns. Each document is self-describing and can have a different structure. Example: MongoDB.'),
('203ee6ac-e5c8-4644-bb3c-855884ba8de4', 'What is a column-family store? Give an example (e.g., Cassandra).', 'A column-family store organizes data into columns and rows, but unlike a relational database, columns can vary by row and are grouped into column families. It''s optimized for queries over large datasets. Example: Apache Cassandra.'),
('203ee6ac-e5c8-4644-bb3c-855884ba8de4', 'What is a graph database? Give an example of a use case.', 'A graph database uses graph structures for semantic queries with nodes, edges, and properties to represent and store data. Example: Social networks (representing people as nodes and friendships as edges) or fraud detection.'),
('203ee6ac-e5c8-4644-bb3c-855884ba8de4', 'What is data replication in a distributed system?', 'Data replication is the process of storing copies of the same data on multiple machines in a distributed system. It provides redundancy, fault tolerance, and improved data availability.'),
('203ee6ac-e5c8-4644-bb3c-855884ba8de4', 'What is data sharding?', 'Data sharding is a database architecture pattern that involves splitting a large dataset horizontally across multiple independent databases (shards). Each shard holds a subset of the data, allowing for horizontal scaling and improved performance.'),
('203ee6ac-e5c8-4644-bb3c-855884ba8de4', 'What is the CAP theorem? Briefly explain Consistency, Availability, and Partition Tolerance.', 'The CAP theorem states that a distributed data store can only provide two of the following three guarantees simultaneously: Consistency (every read receives the most recent write or an error), Availability (every request receives a non-error response), and Partition Tolerance (the system continues to operate despite network partitions).'),
('203ee6ac-e5c8-4644-bb3c-855884ba8de4', 'According to the CAP theorem, what are the two main types of distributed systems?', 'According to the CAP theorem, distributed systems are often classified as either CP (Consistency and Partition Tolerance, sacrificing Availability) or AP (Availability and Partition Tolerance, sacrificing Consistency).'),
('203ee6ac-e5c8-4644-bb3c-855884ba8de4', 'What is cloud computing? How has it impacted Big Data?', 'Cloud computing is the on-demand delivery of IT resources over the internet with pay-as-you-go pricing. It has impacted Big Data by making massive, scalable infrastructure accessible and affordable for any organization.'),
('203ee6ac-e5c8-4644-bb3c-855884ba8de4', 'Briefly explain the difference between IaaS, PaaS, and SaaS.', 'IaaS (Infrastructure as a Service) provides on-demand access to IT infrastructure. PaaS (Platform as a Service) provides a platform for customers to develop, run, and manage applications. SaaS (Software as a Service) provides ready-to-use software over the internet.'),
('203ee6ac-e5c8-4644-bb3c-855884ba8de4', 'Define Data Science. How is it different from traditional statistics?', 'Data Science is an interdisciplinary field that uses scientific methods, algorithms, processes, and systems to extract knowledge and insights from structured and unstructured data. It differs from traditional statistics by its emphasis on large, messy datasets, predictive modeling, and the entire data pipeline.'),
('203ee6ac-e5c8-4644-bb3c-855884ba8de4', 'What is a Data Scientist? What skills does this role typically require?', 'A Data Scientist is a professional who uses their skills in statistics, programming, and domain knowledge to extract insights from data. Skills required: programming (Python/R), statistics/machine learning, data wrangling, and communication.'),
('203ee6ac-e5c8-4644-bb3c-855884ba8de4', 'What is the difference between a Data Scientist and a Data Analyst?', 'A Data Analyst typically focuses on descriptive analytics, visualizing past trends, and creating reports. A Data Scientist focuses on predictive and prescriptive analytics, building complex models to forecast future events and prescribe actions.'),
('203ee6ac-e5c8-4644-bb3c-855884ba8de4', 'What is a Data Engineer? How does their role differ from a Data Scientist''s?', 'A Data Engineer builds and maintains the infrastructure and architecture for data generation, storage, and processing. Their role differs as they focus on the "plumbing" — ensuring data is accessible, clean, and reliable for Data Scientists to analyze.'),
('203ee6ac-e5c8-4644-bb3c-855884ba8de4', 'What is Machine Learning? How is it related to Data Science?', 'Machine Learning is a subset of artificial intelligence that provides systems the ability to automatically learn and improve from experience without being explicitly programmed. It is the primary set of tools and techniques used by Data Scientists to build predictive models.'),
('203ee6ac-e5c8-4644-bb3c-855884ba8de4', 'Name the three main types of machine learning.', 'The three main types are: 1) Supervised Learning, 2) Unsupervised Learning, and 3) Reinforcement Learning.'),
('203ee6ac-e5c8-4644-bb3c-855884ba8de4', 'Describe supervised learning. Give two examples of algorithms.', 'Supervised learning uses labeled datasets to train algorithms to classify data or predict outcomes accurately. Two examples: Linear Regression, Logistic Regression, Decision Trees, Support Vector Machines.'),
('203ee6ac-e5c8-4644-bb3c-855884ba8de4', 'Describe unsupervised learning. Give two examples of algorithms.', 'Unsupervised learning uses algorithms to analyze and cluster unlabeled datasets. Two examples: K-Means Clustering, Hierarchical Clustering, Principal Component Analysis (PCA).'),
('203ee6ac-e5c8-4644-bb3c-855884ba8de4', 'Describe reinforcement learning. Give a real-world example.', 'Reinforcement learning is a type of machine learning where an agent learns to make decisions by interacting with an environment, receiving rewards or penalties. Real-world example: Training a model to play chess or Go, or a robot learning to walk.'),
('203ee6ac-e5c8-4644-bb3c-855884ba8de4', 'What is a model in the context of data science?', 'A model is a specific representation learned from data by applying a machine learning algorithm. It captures patterns and relationships in the data and can be used to make predictions or decisions on new, unseen data.'),
('203ee6ac-e5c8-4644-bb3c-855884ba8de4', 'What is the difference between a feature and a label in supervised learning?', 'A feature is an individual measurable property or characteristic of a phenomenon being observed (the input variable). A label is the target variable that the model is trying to predict (the output).'),
('203ee6ac-e5c8-4644-bb3c-855884ba8de4', 'Define training data.', 'Training data is the initial dataset used to train a machine learning model. The model learns the underlying patterns by seeing the features and their corresponding correct labels (in supervised learning).'),
('203ee6ac-e5c8-4644-bb3c-855884ba8de4', 'Define test/validation data. Why is it important to keep them separate?', 'Test data is a separate, unseen dataset used to evaluate the final performance of a trained model. It is crucial to keep it separate from the training data to get an unbiased estimate of how well the model will perform on new, real-world data.'),
('203ee6ac-e5c8-4644-bb3c-855884ba8de4', 'What is overfitting? Why is it a problem?', 'Overfitting occurs when a model learns the training data too well, including its noise and random fluctuations. It performs well on the training data but poorly on new, unseen data because it has failed to generalize.'),
('203ee6ac-e5c8-4644-bb3c-855884ba8de4', 'What is underfitting?', 'Underfitting occurs when a model is too simple and fails to capture the underlying structure of the data. It performs poorly on both the training data and new data.');